<p style="text-align:right;">Lac Seul<span class="DelHand-author">e</span> June 15<sup>th</sup> 1807.</p>
<p>Sir,</p>
<p class="positiveIndent">I am sorry to inform you that the Themometer you were good enough to lend me in the Summer 1805, was broken by accident here last Summer, so that it was out of my power to keep a satisfactory Journal of the weather, for your perusal, as I fully intended.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Several reasons prevent me from answering the Queries you gave last summer; In the first place, I candidly confess my own inability as a writer; and again Should <span class="AddHand-author">I</span> be inclined to attempt some of them, the scarcity of paper would effectually prevent me.  Although I am perfectly aware, I ca<span class="AddHand-editors">[n]</span> Say nothing on the subject, that is not already generally known, (as I recollect your having Said, that any thing of this nature ought to be done in a letter, to a person supposed to be ignorant of the Country)<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> I shall make a few observations on what comes within my own knowledge, more</p>

